<!--163-->Thin and Stretched<br />
    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#000000">Strategy</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">I’ve been using this deck for about 3 weeks, in both league, a tournament, and play testing. Basically, it kicks butt, particularly Corsairs, which I despise. <br />
You play possessions on Durin, pump him up to huge amounts, then recycle the Honeds on Preparations. Dwarven Axe allows for discarding. Anything that needs set-up becomes completely trashed by Blood Runs Chill. <br />
The shadow is straight Sauron discard. Orc Warriors pitch conditions for 2 cards off the top of your opponent’s draw deck, Desperate Measures takes off 5, and Desperate Defense does the same, or adds burdens. The Shadow side occasionally wins by decking your opponent and spotting 5 burdens, but that’s rare. You want to wipe out your opponent’s draw deck and then triple-move into site 9 with Radagast, if you even need to. Which is how the majority of its victories come, except tripling is rare. Because the dwarves kick butt. <br />
The Morgul Skulker recycles Ferny or Enquea, the rest of the conditions are discard fodder. <br />
 </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#000000"> </Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">DeckTech <BR> For the Players, By the Players  <BR>www.decktech.net </FONT></TD></TR></table> 
